== Roasties and Gravy ==

Preheat your oven to 200°C. Pour a good glug of @oil{} onto a #baking tray{}
and pop in your oven. Bring 2 large #saucepans{} of @water{} to the boil on
high heat with a pinch of @salt{pinch}.

Peel the @potatoes{900%g}, chop them into 4cm chunks. Add the potatoes to
one pan of boiling water and cook for ~{7-8%minutes} or until the edges have
softened when you poke them with a knife.

Peel the @swede{1}, chop into 2 cm chunks and add to the other pan of boiling
water. Cook until tender, ~{20-25%minutes}, then drain in a #colander{} and
return to the #saucepan{}.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}). Pick the
@rosemary{1/2%sprig} leaves from their stalks and finely chop (discard the
stalks). In a #small bowl{}, mix the @panko breadcrumbs{10%g} with the
@grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g}, @ground black pepper{} and a drizzle
of @oil{}. Keep to one side.

Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a colander, pop back into the pan then
sprinkle on half the @plain flour{24%g}. Give your pan a shake to fluff up the
potato.

Take your hot #baking tray{} out of your oven, carefully add your potatoes
in a single layer, turning in the oil. Sprinkle over @salt{pinch}. Roast the
potatoes on the top shelf of your oven for ~{45-50%minutes}, turn halfway
through.

Meanwhile, heat the pan you used for your potatoes over medium heat and add
a splash of @oil{a splash}. Add the @shredded savoy cabbage{150%g}, along with
a splash of @water{a splash} and cook until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}, stirring
frequently.

Add the garlic, cook for ~{1%minute} and then add the @creme fraiche{150%g}.
Bring up to a bubble and carefully stir in the cooked and drained swede. Transfer
to an #ovenproof dish{} and cover with the cheesy crumb. We will bake it later.

Season the @lamb roasting joint{450%g} with @salt{}, @ground black pepper{} and
a drizzle of @oil{}. Transfer to another baking tray and roast in the oven for
~{30-40%minutes} (depending on size) for medium rare.

Add an extra ~{5%minutes} if you like your lamb more cooked. Rest wrapped loosely
in #foil{} for at least ~{10%minutes} before slicing. Time to make the gravy...

Heat a glug of @oil{} in the saucepan you used for the swede over medium heat,
stir in the remaining @plain flour{12%g} and rosemary, cook for ~{1%minute}.

Gradually stir in the @water for the gravy{400%ml} and @balsamic vinegar{12%ml},
bring to the boil, stirring out any lumps that may form.

Stir in the @chicken stock paste{1%tsp}, lower the heat and simmer until the
gravy has thickened to your liking, ~{12-15%minutes}. Season to taste with
@salt{}, @pepper{} and @caster sugar{75%g} if it's a bit sharp.

Pop the swede gratin in the oven and bake for the last ~{10-15%minutes} of
cooking time. You want the top to be crisp and golden.

Do any washing up that needs doing while you have time and reheat the potatoes
or gravy if they have cooled. When everything is hot and ready, remove the
netting from the lamb, slice thinly and arrange on your #plates{}. Pop the
roasties alongside and then spoon out the gratin.

> TIP: Add any resting juices from the lamb to the gravy for extra flavour.

Finish with lashings of gravy and enjoy!

== Mulled Wine Spices ==

Peel the @lemon{1} and @orange{1} with a #potato peeler{}. Halve the orange and
squeeze the juice into a #large saucepan{}, add the lemon and orange peel,
along with the @caster sugar{75%g}, @star anise{1}, @cardamom pod{1} and
@cinnamon stick{1}.

Pour over the @?red wine{750%ml} and heat gently until the sugar has dissolved,
stirring occasionally. Bring to the boil, then remove from the heat and leave
to infuse for ~{15%minutes} (or longer).

When ready to drink, warm it back up and pour into #mugs{} - Enjoy!

> If there's any leftover mulled wine, you can store it in the fridge and reheat
> when you fancy!

> Recipe includes mulled wine spices only. Red wine will not be included with
> your purchase. Let the festivities truly begin!